==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*marha-'', from Indo-European ''*marko-'', horse; cognate with Old Frisian ''[[merie]]'', Old Saxon ''[[merge#Old Saxon|merge]]'' (Dutch ''[[merrie]]''), Old High German ''[[meriha]]'', mare (German ''[[Mähre]]''), Old Norse ''[[merr]]'', ''[[marr]]'' (Swedish ''[[märr]]'').  The IE root is also the source of Irish ''[[marc#Irish|marc]]'' and Welsh ''[[march#Welsh|march]]'', horse

===Pronunciation===
*[[IPA]]: /mæarh/

===Noun===
'''mearh''' ''m'' (''plural'' '''mēares''')

#[[horse]], [[steed]]

